  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation combating money laundering has evolved significantly over the past few decades:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- 1970 Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- First formal regulations requiring financial record-keeping\n- Limited scope of reporting requirements\n\n2. International Developments\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Created global standards for anti-money laundering (AML)\n- Developed recommendations for international cooperation\n\n3. Expansion of Regulations\n- 1990s: Enhanced reporting requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) principles\n- Suspicious transaction reporting mandates\n\n4. Post-9/11 Legislation\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Stricter transaction monitoring\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n\n5. Recent Technological Adaptations\n- Cryptocurrency regulations\n- Digital transaction tracking\n- Enhanced cybersecurity requirements\n- Machine learning and AI-powered monitoring\n\n6. Global Compliance Trends\n- Increased cross-border cooperation\n- Heavier penalties for non-compliance\n- Broader definition of financial institutions\n- More comprehensive risk assessment frameworks\n\nThese legislative developments demonstrate a continuous effort to adapt to evolving financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
